Apr 11, 2015
Becky

        rated it
        it was ok



Transcendence is finding the "true self that longs to live in and through me" (110). Heaven, hell, eternal life, the kingdom of God, etc. are not physical, located in time and space, but "when our mortal life ends, we are freed from the limits of finitude; we enter an eternal space. That is, we join God and exist in the divine state where time and space are no more" (86).Neo-Platonism for post-modern times. The title - "Finding Your Soul" - should have been a clue. Provides insight as to why so
Transcendence is finding the "true self that longs to live in and through me" (110). Heaven, hell, eternal life, the kingdom of God, etc. are not physical, located in time and space, but "when our mortal life ends, we are freed from the limits of finitude; we enter an eternal space. That is, we join God and exist in the divine state where time and space are no more" (86).Neo-Platonism for post-modern times. The title - "Finding Your Soul" - should have been a clue. Provides insight as to why so many in the Episcopal church no longer believe in the physical birth, resurrection and return of Jesus Christ. Two stars for an occasional interesting insight and some good, stand-alone quotes from other authors.
